<p>If you need any other information please let me know.</p>  <p><strong>Short Version:</strong></p>  <p>This line of code causes a NullPointerException when tested with jUnit 4.12:</p>  <pre><code>File[] files = new File(searchPath).listFiles(); </code></pre>  <p><strong>Long version:</strong></p>  <p>First of all, this is the enviroment:</p>  <ul> <li>OS: Win7 Pro (Netbeans runs as Admin)</li> <li>IDE: Netbeans 8.0.2</li> <li>Build automation tool: Gradle</li> <li>Java: JDK 1.8</li> <li>Test-Framework: jUnit 4.12</li> </ul>  <p>The exception only occurs when i run jUnit-tests. When i build it without any tests, everything works fine and the function <em>listFiles()</em> from <em>File[] files = new File(searchPath).listFiles()</em> doesn't return null.</p>  <pre><code>gradle clean &amp; gradle build -x test &amp; gradle rest:jettyRun 2&gt; test.txt </code></pre>  <p>This is the problem-function, called in the constructor of my class:</p>  <pre><code>/**  * Scans for JSON files on given path  * @param searchPath full path given  * @return String[] with the full paths and names of found files  */ private String[] scanForJsons(String searchPath){     System.out.println("search path "+searchPath); // shows D:\..\core\files      File[] files = new File(searchPath).listFiles(); // problem line, allways returns null      System.out.print(((files!=null)?"Not null" : "Null"));     System.out.println("files.length: "+files.length);     String[] stringArray = new String[files.length];      for(int i = 0; i &lt; files.length; i++){         String path = files[i].getName();         if (path.endsWith(".json")) {             path = path.substring(0, path.length() - 5);         }         stringArray[i] = path;     }     return stringArray; } </code></pre>